04/03/2023 at 20:12:40 PDT

A snippet: Oliver's heart sinks as he watches Kogan slump against the wall, eyes unfocused while his head slowly lists to the side. "You're exhausted," Oliver says, his voice gentle, "You need to sleep." Kogan's tired eyes blink sluggishly as he mumbles, "I am asleep..." "You know what I mean...," Oliver replies, "Your brain needs a break - ever heard of the Russian sleep experiment?” Kogan scoffs quietly, “'s not even real..." “Yeah, well, that hasn’t stopped anything else in here from killing us.” Oliver counters. Kogan hums in response and wearily adjusts his posture to sit up straighter against the wall for what feels like the hundredth time. “What do you want me to do about it?" Kogan sighs, "I’m aware of the physiological need for sleep. But this place won't let me.” Oliver chews his lip. “I’ve been thinking about that, actually. I might have an idea.” Kogan doesn't react which is no surprise. Kogan rarely shows enthusiasm for Oliver’s ideas. Before he can lose his nerve, Oliver launches into a speech about scientific studies that have found physical contact to increase oxytocin in the brain, and how that triggers the release of serotonin and other natural anti-anxiety hormones - perfect for fighting off nightmares. He also mentions how meditation has been demonstrated to further alleviate stress levels and enable the brain to enter a restorative state. Kogan's previously heavy eyes are staring up at him in open astonishment as though Oliver is sporting a second head, but Oliver doesn't let that distract him as he continues to build his case. By now, Oliver knows Kogan well enough to understand that his offer of help will have a better chance of being accepted if he introduces the concept gradually, through empirical evidence. "Oliver," Kogan interrupts and Oliver falls silent as Kogan peers at him with a mix of suspicion and a pinch of hope - or perhaps that was Oliver's own imagination. "What did you have in mind?" Kogan finally asks. It was the opening Oliver had been hoping for and he feels his heart beat with anticipation. Slowly, cautiously, as if attempting to persuade a timid animal not to flee, Oliver holds his hand out for Kogan, “Come here," he whispers, "Lay down with me."

Tara (Toonimated)

05/01/2023 at 20:55:29 PDT

Kogan awoke to the musty smell of the broom closet, his body aching from the cramped and uncomfortable position he had spent the night in. His head pounded as fragmented memories of something chasing him flashed through his mind. Rubbing his eyes, he searched his pockets for his journal. Frustration bubbled inside him as he flipped through the pages, finding no new entry to explain the situation. With a resigned sigh, he carefully opened the closet door, peering out into the hallway. The early morning light filtering through the windows told him it was morning, but he had no idea what time it was. He'd dropped his phone at some point last night while he was running away from... whatever that thing was. Kogan stepped out of the closet, careful not to make any noise. The last thing he wanted was for someone to discover he had spent the night there. If he could reach his office, he could clean himself up in the attached bathroom before facing anyone. Just as he began to tiptoe down the hall, a voice called out his name. Startled, Kogan looked around to find Oliver standing there, a confused expression on his face. "I thought I told you not to film here!" Kogan snapped, his heart racing. Oliver's confusion deepened. "You hired me...," he said hesitantly. Kogan's mind reeled as the memory surfaced. He had hired Oliver, but the memory was blurry... he hadn't been himself at the time. And Oliver definitely didn't need to know that. "Right, of course," Kogan said, his voice tense. "I must've... forgotten. There's been a lot going on." Oliver eyed him with concern. "Are you feeling okay? Did you even go home last night?" Kogan's heart skipped a beat as Oliver's gaze drifted toward the broom closet, seemingly piecing the puzzle together. "No!" Kogan shouted a little too loudly, but at least Oliver was looking at him again, eyebrows raised high. "I mean, yes." Kogan corrected. Then, grasping for some excuse or distraction, he gestured down the hallway. "Listen, I need you to check the security footage on the third floor. And ask the tenants if they've seen any... strange bugs." "Strange bugs..." Oliver repeated with a small frown on his face. Kogan didn't wait for follow-up questions as he turned and practically sprinted toward his office. The weight of his situation pressed down on Kogan as he closed the door behind him. He was slipping. His carefully constructed facade was splintering under the pressure of whatever was going on in this building and he wasn't sure how much longer his secret would be safe.

I wonder when (in the pintv timeline) that recording was taken if it's on a cassette tape. Since, so far, it seems pintv has a contemporary setting, cassette tapes are considered rather dated technology by today's standards. Cassette tapes were first invented in the mid 60s and were considered the standard audio format from the late 70s through the early 90s. So, unless the doctor (at least I presume that's who the man's voice was) for some reason prefers to use dated technology, that recording is old.
